    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. Parse the timestamp columns with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). For each file, return a compact summary: total number of rows, distinct cmdb_id values (list up to 50), and distinct KPI/feature/log name values with counts (for metric.csv use kpi_name, for trace.csv use trace_name, for log.csv use log_name). For error_logs.csv, return distinct cmdb_id and the top 20 messages (with counts) sorted by frequency. Keep outputs bounded (at most 50 distinct names and top 20 messages). Do not print full tables; only return these aggregates."
}

{
    "analysis": "Loaded telemetry files summary received: metric.csv (1925 rows, 15 components, 8 KPI types), trace.csv empty, log.csv (458 rows, 12 components, 2 log types), error_logs.csv empty. No further analysis done yet. Next we must compute global thresholds per component-KPI (using full metric series) before filtering to the incident window, per the diagnosis workflow.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global statistics over the full available series: count, mean, min, max, p95, p90, p5. Store the aggregated table in the kernel. Return a compact table limited to the top 50 rows sorted by p95 descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, mean, min, max, p95, p90, p5. Also return the total number of unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global statistics (count, mean, min, max, p95, p90, p5) per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) over the full metric series and inspected the top entries by p95. Next we must detect anomalies inside the incident window using those global thresholds. Based on available KPI names (cpu, mem, socket, latency-50, workload, latency-90, diskio, error), treat workload as a traffic/business KPI where sudden drops are anomalies (use <= p5), and treat the others as resource/latency KPIs where spikes are anomalies (use >= p95). We will now scan the incident window (2024-01-18 19:28:30 to 2024-01-18 19:58:30 UTC) and find which component-KPIs breach their global thresholds, with compact aggregates to prioritize candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Using the previously stored global aggregate table (agg_metric) that contains p95 and p5 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name), filter metric rows to the incident window from 2024-01-18 19:28:30 UTC to 2024-01-18 19:58:30 UTC inclusive. Classify KPI anomaly direction: treat 'workload' as low-is-bad (anomaly if value <= p5); treat all other KPIs as high-is-bad (anomaly if value >= p95). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) produce a compact aggregate: anomaly_count (number of points in window breaching threshold), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), latest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, severity_metric where for high-is-bad compute max_value_in_window / p95, and for workload compute p5 / min_value_in_window. Return the top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_metric desc, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p5, severity_metric. Also return the total number of (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs that had anomaly_count > 0."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous anomaly scan: metric analysis found widespread socket KPI breaches across many services during the incident window (many components show socket values at their historical p95 for every minute in the window). A smaller set of high-severity anomalies exists (notably shipping latency-90 with a very large breach, shipping CPU spikes, and orders error spikes). trace.csv and error_logs.csv are empty, so we cannot use traces or error log messages to disambiguate. Given the broad socket anomalies across many services, the leading hypothesis is a network/socket level problem (socket error / network packet loss / network latency) that affected many components; the shipping service also experienced a pronounced latency spike which may be an effect or a local problem. To decide whether the root cause is network-level or a single service (e.g., shipping or rabbitmq), we must check application logs for error counts during the window to see which services reported application-level errors or increases in error_count that coincide with metric anomalies.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and parse timestamps with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Filter log rows to the incident window 2024-01-18 19:28:30 UTC through 2024-01-18 19:58:30 UTC inclusive. For each cmdb_id, aggregate per log_name: compute sum(value) and count(rows), earliest timestamp, latest timestamp. Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, sum_log_error_count (sum of value where log_name=='log.error_count'), sum_log_row_count (sum of value where log_name=='log.row_count'), rows_in_window (total rows for that cmdb_id), earliest_timestamp (UTC), latest_timestamp (UTC). Sort the table by sum_log_error_count descending then rows_in_window descending. Also return the list of cmdb_id values where sum_log_error_count > 0 (if any). Keep outputs bounded (max 20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing and metric-based anomaly detection. Summary of findings so far: metric analysis shows widespread socket KPI breaches across many services during the incident window (most socket values equal their historical p95 for the full window), plus a small set of high-severity outliers (notably shipping latency-90 and shipping CPU spikes). trace.csv and error_logs.csv are empty, so we cannot use traces or error messages to disambiguate. Log analysis shows high request/log volume in front-end, user, queue-master, orders and catalogue, but no recorded log.error_count > 0 in the incident window. Given the broad socket anomalies spanning many services, the leading hypothesis is a network/socket-level issue. However, the root-cause component to report must be one of the candidate services (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user). To choose among them we need focused metric evidence (earliest/most severe anomalies) for these candidate services. Therefore we should extract per-KPI anomaly aggregates restricted to the five candidate components within the incident window to see which candidate shows the earliest or most significant fault.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter metric.csv to the incident window 2024-01-18 19:28:30 UTC through 2024-01-18 19:58:30 UTC and to cmdb_id in [carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user]. Using the previously computed global thresholds per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) (p95 and p5), classify anomalies (workload low-is-bad using <=p5; all other KPIs high-is-bad using >=p95). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute: anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), latest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p5, and severity_metric (for high-is-bad: max_value_in_window / p95; for workload: p5 / min_value_in_window). Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_metric desc with those columns. Also return which of these candidate components has the earliest anomaly timestamp among all their KPIs (and that timestamp). Keep outputs bounded."
}
